Duchenne muscular dystrophy, an X-linked disorder, has an incidence of one in 
5000 boys and presents in early childhood with proximal muscle weakness. 
Untreated boys become wheelchair bound by the age of 12 years and die of 
cardiorespiratory complications in their late teens to early 20s. The use of 
corticosteroids, non-invasive respiratory support, and active surveillance and 
management of associated complications have improved ambulation, function, 
quality of life and life expectancy. The clinical features, investigations and 
management of Duchenne muscular dystrophy are reviewed, as well as the latest in 
some of the novel therapies.

